The event loop is what allows Node.js to perform non-blocking I/O operations.

## How the Event Loop Works

1. Timers: executes setTimeout, setInterval callbacks
2. Pending callbacks: I/O callbacks deferred to next iteration
3. Idle, prepare: internal use
4. Poll: retrieve new I/O events
5. Check: setImmediate callbacks
6. Close callbacks: close event callbacks

## Event Emitter
```javascript
const EventEmitter = require('events');

class MyEmitter extends EventEmitter {}

const myEmitter = new MyEmitter();

myEmitter.on('event', () => {
    console.log('Event occurred!');
});

myEmitter.emit('event');
```

## Async Patterns
```javascript
// Callbacks (traditional)
fs.readFile('file.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
    if (err) return console.error(err);
    console.log(data);
});

// Promises
const readFilePromise = (filename) => {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        fs.readFile(filename, 'utf8', (err, data) => {
            if (err) reject(err);
            else resolve(data);
        });
    });
};

// Async/Await
async function processFile() {
    try {
        const data = await readFilePromise('file.txt');
        const modified = data.toUpperCase();
        await writeFilePromise('output.txt', modified);
        console.log('Process complete');
    } catch (err) {
        console.error(err);
    }
}
```

## process.nextTick vs setImmediate
```javascript
process.nextTick(() => {
    console.log('Executed before next event loop iteration');
});

setImmediate(() => {
    console.log('Executed in the check phase');
});
```

Understanding the event loop is crucial for Node.js performance.

