Schema design is crucial for MongoDB performance and maintainability.

## Embedding vs Referencing

### Embedding (Denormalization)
```javascript
// User with embedded addresses
{
  _id: ObjectId(),
  name: 'Alice',
  addresses: [
    { type: 'home', street: '123 Main St', city: 'NYC' },
    { type: 'work', street: '456 Office Blvd', city: 'NYC' }
  ]
}
```

Use when: data is accessed together, rarely changes, small size.

### Referencing (Normalization)
```javascript
// User document
{
  _id: ObjectId(),
  name: 'Alice'
}

// Order document (references user)
{
  _id: ObjectId(),
  userId: ObjectId(),
  total: 100.50,
  items: [...]
}
```

Use when: data grows independently, large documents, many-to-many.

## Design Patterns

### One-to-One
```javascript
// Embed directly
{ user: { name: 'Alice', profile: { avatar: 'url', bio: 'Bio' } } }
```

### One-to-Many
```javascript
// Embed (few items)
{ user: { name: 'Alice', addresses: [...] } }

// Reference (many items)
// User: { _id, name }
// Orders: [{ userId, total, items }]
```

### Many-to-Many
```javascript
// Students and Courses
// Student: { _id, name, courseIds: [ObjectId, ObjectId] }
// Course: { _id, name, studentIds: [ObjectId] }
```

## Bucketing Pattern
```javascript
// Group related data by time periods
{
  sensorId: ObjectId(),
  hour: ISODate('2026-01-01T00:00:00Z'),
  readings: [
    { time: '00:01', value: 23 },
    { time: '00:02', value: 24 }
  ]
}
```

Good schema design is key to MongoDB application success.

