MongoDB provides high availability and scalability through replication and sharding.

## Replication (Replica Sets)
A replica set is a group of MongoDB servers maintaining the same data.

### Architecture
```
Primary (handles writes)
├── Secondary 1 (read-only copy)
├── Secondary 2 (read-only copy)
└── Arbiter (voting only)
```

### Setup
```javascript
// mongod.conf for each node
replication:
  replSetName: "rs0"

// Initiate replica set
rs.initiate({
  _id: "rs0",
  members: [
    { _id: 0, host: "localhost:27017" },
    { _id: 1, host: "localhost:27018" },
    { _id: 2, host: "localhost:27019", arbiterOnly: true }
  ]
});
```

### Read from Secondaries
```javascript
// In Mongoose
mongoose.connect(url, { readPreference: 'secondaryPreferred' });
```

## Sharding
Horizontal scaling by distributing data across multiple servers.

### Components
- Config Servers (metadata)
- Mongos (router)
- Shards (data storage)

### Shard Key Selection
```javascript
// Good shard key: high cardinality, evenly distributed
sh.shardCollection("mydb.users", { _id: "hashed" });

// Range-based sharding
sh.shardCollection("mydb.orders", { createdAt: 1 });

// Zone sharding (geographic)
sh.addShardTag("shard01", "US");
sh.addTagRange("mydb.users", { country: "US" }, { country: "US" }, "US");
```

## Choosing the Right Strategy

- Replication: High availability, disaster recovery
- Sharding: Large datasets, high throughput
- Both: Maximum scalability and reliability

MongoDB's scaling features make it suitable for enterprise applications.

Change streams allow applications to watch real-time changes in MongoDB.

## What are Change Streams?
They provide real-time notifications of database changes without polling.

## Basic Usage
```javascript
const changeStream = db.collection('orders').watch();

changeStream.on('change', (change) => {
    console.log('Change detected:', change);

    switch (change.operationType) {
        case 'insert':
            console.log('New document:', change.fullDocument);
            break;
        case 'update':
            console.log('Updated fields:', change.updateDescription);
            break;
        case 'delete':
            console.log('Deleted document ID:', change.documentKey);
            break;
        case 'replace':
            console.log('Replaced document:', change.fullDocument);
            break;
    }
});
```

## Pipeline and Filters
```javascript
// Watch specific documents
const pipeline = [
    { $match: { 'fullDocument.status': 'pending' } }
];

const changeStream = db.collection('orders').watch(pipeline);
```

## Resume Tokens
```javascript
// Save resume token for recovery
let resumeToken = null;

const changeStream = db.collection('orders').watch();

changeStream.on('change', (change) => {
    resumeToken = change._id;
    // Process change...
});

// Resume from last token (if connection drops)
const resumedStream = db.collection('orders').watch([], { resumeAfter: resumeToken });
```

## Integration with Node.js
```javascript
// Notify connected clients
const WebSocket = require('ws');
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

const changeStream = db.collection('orders').watch();

changeStream.on('change', (change) => {
    wss.clients.forEach((client) => {
        if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
            client.send(JSON.stringify(change));
        }
    });
});
```

## Use Cases
- Real-time dashboards
- Notifications
- Data synchronization
- Audit logging
- Cache invalidation

Change streams enable reactive, event-driven architectures with MongoDB.

