API versioning allows your API to evolve without breaking existing clients.

## Why Version APIs?
- Maintain backward compatibility
- Allow gradual migration
- Communicate breaking changes
- Support multiple client versions

## URI Versioning
```
GET /api/v1/users
GET /api/v2/users

// Implementation
app.use('/api/v1', v1Router);
app.use('/api/v2', v2Router);
```

## Header Versioning
```javascript
// Client sends header
Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v1+json
Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v2+json

// Express middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    const version = req.headers['accept']?.match(/vnd[.]myapi[.]v([.]+)/)?.[1];
    req.apiVersion = parseInt(version) || 1;
    next();
});
```

## Query Parameter Versioning
```
GET /api/users?version=1
GET /api/users?version=2
```

## Versioning Strategy

### During Development
```javascript
// Version 1 (original)
router.get('/users', v1Controller.getUsers);

// Version 2 (added pagination)
router.get('/users', v2Controller.getUsers);
```

### Deprecation Flow
```javascript
app.use('/api/v1/users', (req, res, next) => {
    res.set('X-API-Deprecated', 'true');
    res.set('X-API-Sunset', 'Wed, 01 Jan 2027 00:00:00 GMT');
    next();
}, v1UsersRouter);
```

## Best Practices

1. **Document changes clearly**
   - Changelog for each version
   - Migration guides

2. **Support overlapping versions**
   - Allow time for migration (6+ months)
   - Run multiple versions simultaneously

3. **Use semantic versioning**
   - Major: Breaking changes
   - Minor: New features (backward compatible)
   - Patch: Bug fixes

4. **Communicate deprecation**
   - Add deprecation headers
   - Announce via changelog
   - Email notification for breaking changes

## Migration Example
```javascript
// Old parameter
GET /api/users?page=1

// New parameter (with backward compatibility)
router.get('/users', (req, res) => {
    const page = req.query.page || req.query.offset || 1;
    const limit = req.query.limit || req.query.per_page || 10;
    // ...
});
```

Good versioning strategy prevents breaking changes from affecting users.

WebSockets provide full-duplex communication channels over a single TCP connection.

## WebSocket vs HTTP
- HTTP: Request-response, stateless
- WebSocket: Persistent connection, bidirectional, real-time

## WebSocket API with ws library
```javascript
const WebSocket = require('ws');
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

wss.on('connection', (ws, req) => {
    console.log('Client connected');

    // Send welcome message
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'welcome', message: 'Connected!' }));

    // Handle messages
    ws.on('message', (data) => {
        const message = JSON.parse(data);

        switch (message.type) {
            case 'chat':
                // Broadcast to all clients
                wss.clients.forEach(client => {
                    if (client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
                        client.send(JSON.stringify({
                            type: 'chat',
                            user: message.user,
                            text: message.text,
                            timestamp: Date.now()
                        }));
                    }
                });
                break;
            case 'subscribe':
                // Join a room/topic
                ws.room = message.room;
                break;
        }
    });

    // Handle disconnect
    ws.on('close', () => {
        console.log('Client disconnected');
    });
});
```

## Client-Side WebSocket
```javascript
const ws = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8080');

ws.onopen = () => {
    console.log('Connected to server');
    ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'chat', user: 'Alice', text: 'Hello!' }));
};

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
    console.log('Received:', data);
};

ws.onclose = () => {
    console.log('Disconnected from server');
};

// Reconnection logic
function connect() {
    const ws = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8080');

    ws.onclose = () => {
        console.log('Reconnecting in 5 seconds...');
        setTimeout(connect, 5000);
    };

    ws.onerror = (err) => {
        console.error('WebSocket error:', err);
        ws.close();
    };
}
```

## Use Cases
- Real-time chat
- Live notifications
- Collaborative editing
- Stock tickers
- Gaming
- Live dashboards

WebSockets enable real-time features that HTTP alone cannot provide efficiently.

An API gateway acts as a single entry point for all client requests in a microservices architecture.

